SUMMARY:A Celebration of Life for Rich Peck
DESCRIPTION:Rich served as an Associate Professor of International Affair
 s from 1974 until his retirement in 2008. After completing his undergradu
 ate degree at the University of California Berkeley and his graduate stud
 ies at Yale\, he brought a profound global perspective to our campus\, pr
 imarily through his dedicated teaching on the cultures and politics of Af
 rica and Southeast Asia.  Professor Peck's impact on Lewis &amp\; Clark w
 as perhaps most visible through his work with the study abroad programs. 
 He was instrumental in expanding our reach into East Africa\, leading tri
 ps in 1978 and 2010\, and sharing his passion for international engagemen
 t by leading programs to Ecuador in 1986 and Argentina in 1988. Even afte
 r his formal retirement\, Rich remained connected with the Lewis &amp\; C
 lark community. Living just a short distance from campus\, he continued t
 o support our global mission by hosting foreign exchange students for the
  past several years.  For those who wish to read more about his remarkabl
 e life and contributions\, please see Rich's formal obituary: &#160\;http
 s://everloved.com/life-of/richard-peck/obituary/ (https://everloved.com/l
 ife-of/richard-peck/obituary/). A link to Watzek Library special collecti
 ons oral history interview can be found here (https://specialcollections.
 lclark.edu/items/show/1387).
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p dir="ltr">  Rich served as an Associate P
 rofessor of International Affairs from 1974 until his retirement in 2008.
  After completing his undergraduate degree at the University of Californi
 a Berkeley and his graduate studies at Yale\, he brought a profound globa
 l perspective to our campus\, primarily through his dedicated teaching on
  the cultures and politics of Africa and Southeast Asia.</p><p dir="ltr">
   Professor Peck's impact on Lewis &amp\; Clark was perhaps most visible 
 through his work with the study abroad programs. He was instrumental in e
 xpanding our reach into East Africa\, leading trips in 1978 and 2010\, an
 d sharing his passion for international engagement by leading programs to
  Ecuador in 1986 and Argentina in 1988. Even after his formal retirement\
 , Rich remained connected with the Lewis &amp\; Clark community. Living j
 ust a short distance from campus\, he continued to support our global mis
 sion by hosting foreign exchange students for the past several years.</p>
 <p dir="ltr">  For those who wish to read more about his remarkable life 
 and contributions\, please see Rich's formal obituary: &#160\;<a href="ht
 tps://everloved.com/life-of/richard-peck/obituary/">https://everloved.com
 /life-of/richard-peck/obituary/</a>. A link to Watzek Library special col
 lections oral history interview can be found <a href="https://specialcoll
 ections.lclark.edu/items/show/1387" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-s
 aferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://specialcollections.l
 clark.edu/items/show/1387&amp\;source=gmail&amp\;ust=1774539104620000&amp
 \;usg=AOvVaw37VLi-x_Ft2KtFU0BBNxfC">here</a>.</p>
