SUMMARY:A Celebration of Life for Molly Robinson
DESCRIPTION:A beloved professor\, colleague\, advisor\, and friend\, Moll
 y Robinson will be dearly missed by the Lewis &amp\; Clark community. She
  was a cornerstone of the World Languages and Literatures Department and 
 the French Section\, and was a vibrant\, engaged\, fiercely dedicated mem
 ber of the larger college. In recent years\, she poured her heart into im
 proving pedagogy through her work as Director of the Teaching Excellence 
 Program (TEP)\, but her contributions extended far and deep throughout th
 e institution\, as evidenced by her winning the David Savage Award in 202
 2. To her students\, whether in her classes or at the Mossy Log student n
 ewspaper\, where she served as Faculty Advisor for over a dozen years\, s
 he was a mentor\, advocate\, wise counsel\, and enthusiastic believer in 
 every student's potential.Molly arrived at Lewis &amp\; Clark in 2004\, h
 aving received candidature and licence degrees from the Universit├® Catho
 lique de Louvain in Belgium\, and her PhD in Romance Languages and Lite
 ratures from Princeton\, with a specialization in medieval French literat
 ure. Her book\, The Hero's Place: Medieval Literary Traditions of Space a
 nd Belonging\, was published in 2009\, and numerous articles followed\, o
 n her much-loved medieval tales or more recent work on Gustave Flaubert a
 nd Oscar Wilde. She taught widely across the curriculum\, from Core cours
 es to an Inside-Out section titled "The Cry of Freedom" in 2023.Molly lov
 ed the Lewis &amp\; Clark community deeply\, and that love was reciprocat
 ed by colleagues\, friends\, and students across the campus. She was a sp
 iritual and caring person that left everyone she met feeling as though th
 ey truly mattered. Her love of nature and culture celebrated their abunda
 nce.Molly is survived by her husband Joel Pomije\, step-son Elijah\, her 
 parents Steven and Margaret Robinson\, her younger siblings Meg and Joe\,
  sister-in-law Alicia\, niece Maizie\, nephews Max and Marshall\, her bel
 oved children Atticus and Miriam\, and their father Gordon.  Optionally\,
  guests are invited to RSVP to assist with an accurate guest count for th
 e day. Thank you!Thanks to Bruce Suttmeier for much of this announcement.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p dir="ltr">  A beloved professor\, colleag
 ue\, advisor\, and friend\, <span class="il">Molly</span> Robinson will b
 e dearly missed by the Lewis &amp\; Clark community. She was a cornerston
 e of the World Languages and Literatures Department and the French Sectio
 n\, and was a vibrant\, engaged\, fiercely dedicated member of the larger
  college. In recent years\, she poured her heart into improving pedagogy 
 through her work as Director of the Teaching Excellence Program (TEP)\, b
 ut her contributions extended far and deep throughout the institution\, a
 s evidenced by her winning the David Savage Award in 2022. To her student
 s\, whether in her classes or at the Mossy Log student newspaper\, where 
 she served as Faculty Advisor for over a dozen years\, she was a mentor\,
  advocate\, wise counsel\, and enthusiastic believer in every student's p
 otential.</p><p dir="ltr"><span class="il">Molly</span> arrived at Lewis 
 &amp\; Clark in 2004\, having received candidature and licence degrees fr
 om the Universit├® Catholique de Louvain in Belgium\, and her PhD in Ro
 mance Languages and Literatures from Princeton\, with a specialization in
  medieval French literature. Her book\, The Hero's Place: Medieval Litera
 ry Traditions of Space and Belonging\, was published in 2009\, and numero
 us articles followed\, on her much-loved medieval tales or more recent wo
 rk on Gustave Flaubert and Oscar Wilde. She taught widely across the curr
 iculum\, from Core courses to an Inside-Out section titled "The Cry of Fr
 eedom" in 2023.</p><p dir="ltr"><span class="il">Molly</span> loved the L
 ewis &amp\; Clark community deeply\, and that love was reciprocated by co
 lleagues\, friends\, and students across the campus. She was a spiritual 
 and caring person that left everyone she met feeling as though they truly
  mattered. Her love of nature and culture celebrated their abundance.</p>
 <p dir="ltr"><span class="il">Molly</span> is survived by her husband Joe
 l Pomije\, step-son Elijah\, her parents Steven and Margaret Robinson\, h
 er younger siblings Meg and Joe\, sister-in-law Alicia\, niece Maizie\, n
 ephews Max and Marshall\, her beloved children Atticus and Miriam\, and t
 heir father Gordon.</p><p dir="ltr">  Optionally\, guests are invited to 
 RSVP to assist with an accurate guest count for the day. Thank you!</p><p
  dir="ltr"><em>Thanks to Bruce Suttmeier for much of this announcement.</
 em></p>
