LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Neurodiverse Relationships: Using IFS to Support Mixed Neurotype 
 Partnerships (Online)
DESCRIPTION:In the last decade\, societal awareness of and research cente
 ring neurodiversity (ND) have become more commonplace. As a result\, an i
 ncreasing number of our clients are self-identifying as and/or receiving 
 diagnoses of Autism\, ADHD\, and any of a number of other ND diagnoses (e
 .g. OCD\, Bipolar\, Schizophrenia\, etc.).  As we apply what we know abou
 t how neurological differences affect folx's ability to navigate and thri
 ve in a world that has been designed by and for neuro-normative brains\, 
 it is essential that we know how to support our ND clients in successfull
 y cultivating their intimate relationships given their unique challenges.
   This workshop will provide an overview of common neurological differenc
 es and addresses the way they shape how our ND clients navigate interpers
 onal\, particularly intimate\, relationships. We differentiate between ne
 urological differences that cannot be changed\, and maladaptive emotional
  patterns that can be healed. In relationships where one or more partners
  are ND\, we identify common areas of misunderstanding\, misattunement\, 
 or lack of connection.  Using an Internal Family Systems (IFS) framework\
 , we explore how an understanding of clients' Self and parts can help the
 m navigate intimate relationships with greater self-knowledge and an impr
 oved ability to have meaningful\, Self-to-Self connection.  Prior experie
 nce with IFS is helpful but not necessary to benefit from this workshop.F
 ollowing this workshop\, participants will have an increased understandin
 g of:      How neurological differences in neurodiverse folx may impact t
 he way they relate to\, connect with\, and understand intimate partners i
 n mixed neurotype relationships          Common misunderstandings and cha
 llenges that may arise in relationships with mixed neurotypes          Di
 fferences between "hardware" (neurology) and "software" (aka the burdens 
 that "parts" carry) in neurodiverse folx\, to determine which traits requ
 ire accommodations\, and which can be worked with          How to apply a
  basic understanding of IFS to help clients navigate their intimate relat
 ionships      This workshop may meet the OBLPCT Cultural Competence Conti
 nuing Education requirement. Click here for more information (http://www.
 oregon.gov/oblpct/Pages/CCCE.aspx)Details &amp\; RegistrationDate and Tim
 e: Wednesday\, April 8\, 2026\, 12-3 p.m. PT\, OnlinePresenter:&#160\;Reg
 ina Wei\, LMFTCost and Credits: $79\, includes 3 CEUs. GSEC Alumni and Ad
 juncts save 20%. $40 student rate.&#160\;  No-cost registrations availabl
 e for GSEC Faculty\, Staff\, and Clinical Mental Health Supervisors. Emai
 l cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu) to register.Register Online (htt
 ps://lclark.tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY0000022GCP)Registration ends a
 fter Sunday\, April 5thAccessibility: We are committed to making our even
 ts accessible to all needs and abilities. When registering\, please let u
 s know your access needs. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (m
 ailto:cce@lclark.edu)&#160\;with questions.Please note: Discounted &#x201
 8\;Student Rate&#x2019\; registrations are for current students only and 
 do not include continuing education credit (CEU/PDUs)About the Instructor
 Regina Wei\, LMFT (https://www.reginawei.com/) (she/they)\, is an IFS tra
 ined therapist in WA with specializations in sex therapy and psychedelic 
 assisted therapy (PAT). Their practice prioritizes folx who identify as B
 IPOC\, LGBTQIA+\, and/or neurodiverse. Regina's work is informed by a dee
 p commitment to social justice and is focused on healing racial\, interge
 nerational\, sexual\, and other traumas. Their background includes teachi
 ng meditation/mindfulness\, yoga\, and energy healing in addition to over
  15 years of experience in classroom teaching.  Before working as a thera
 pist\, Regina served for two years as one of the main DEIJ (diversity\, e
 quity\, inclusion and justice) practitioners at an independent school whe
 re they helped facilitate DEIJ conversations among students\, faculty\, a
 nd administration\, co-led a DEIJ task force\, and was a member of the hi
 ring committee for the school's new Director of Equity.&#160\;New worksho
 ps and trainings are added to our calendar regularly. For the latest on p
 rofessional development related to your specific interests\, sign up for 
 our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  In the last 
 decade\, societal awareness of and research centering neurodiversity (ND)
  have become more commonplace. As a result\, an increasing number of our 
 clients are self-identifying as and/or receiving diagnoses of Autism\, AD
 HD\, and any of a number of other ND diagnoses (e.g. OCD\, Bipolar\, Schi
 zophrenia\, etc.).</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  As we apply what we
  know about how neurological differences affect folx's ability to navigat
 e and thrive in a world that has been designed by and for neuro-normative
  brains\, it is essential that we know how to support our ND clients in s
 uccessfully cultivating their intimate relationships given their unique c
 hallenges.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This workshop will provide 
 an overview of common neurological differences and addresses the way they
  shape how our ND clients navigate interpersonal\, particularly intimate\
 , relationships. We differentiate between neurological differences that c
 annot be changed\, and maladaptive emotional patterns that can be healed.
  In relationships where one or more partners are ND\, we identify common 
 areas of misunderstanding\, misattunement\, or lack of connection.</p><p 
 style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Using an Internal Family Systems (IFS) frame
 work\, we explore how an understanding of clients' Self and parts can hel
 p them navigate intimate relationships with greater self-knowledge and an
  improved ability to have meaningful\, Self-to-Self connection.</p><p sty
 le="line-height: 1.5\;">  Prior experience with IFS is helpful but not ne
 cessary to benefit from this workshop.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><
 strong>Following this workshop\, participants will have an increased unde
 rstanding of:</strong></p><ul><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      How
  neurological differences in neurodiverse folx may impact the way they re
 late to\, connect with\, and understand intimate partners in mixed neurot
 ype relationships    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Com
 mon misunderstandings and challenges that may arise in relationships with
  mixed neurotypes    </p></li><li><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">      Dif
 ferences between "hardware" (neurology) and "software" (aka the burdens t
 hat "parts" carry) in neurodiverse folx\, to determine which traits requi
 re accommodations\, and which can be worked with    </p></li><li><p style
 ="line-height: 1.5\;">      How to apply a basic understanding of IFS to 
 help clients navigate their intimate relationships    </p></li></ul><p st
 yle="line-height: 1.5\;">  This workshop may meet the OBLPCT Cultural Com
 petence Continuing Education requirement. <a href="http://www.oregon.gov/
 oblpct/Pages/CCCE.aspx">Click here for more information</a></p><hr /><h2>
 <strong>Details &amp\; Registration</strong></h2><p style="line-height: 1
 .5\;"><strong>Date and Time:</strong> Wednesday\, April 8\, 2026\, 12-3 p
 .m. PT\, Online</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Presenter:</stro
 ng>&#160\;Regina Wei\, LMFT</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Cost
  and Credits:</strong> $79\, includes 3 CEUs. GSEC Alumni and Adjuncts sa
 ve 20%. $40 student rate.&#160\;</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  No-co
 st registrations available for GSEC Faculty\, Staff\, and Clinical Mental
  Health Supervisors. Email <a href="mailto:cce@lclark.edu">cce@lclark.edu
 </a> to register.</p><p><a class="btn-small-style-1" href="https://lclark
 .tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY0000022GCP" target="_blank" rel="noopener
 ">Register Online</a></p><p><em><strong>Registration ends after Sunday\, 
 April 5th</strong></em></p><div id="lw_widget_30f0017c" class="lw_widget 
 lw_widget_type_blurbs lw_widget_blurbs lw_widget_id_7119 lw_widget_access
 ibility_statement lw_widget_pagination"><ul class="lw_widget_results lw_w
