DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260410T160000
LOCATION:Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School of Education and Counseling\,
  South Chapel
SUMMARY:Movement & Creativity for Trauma Resolution (In-Person)
DESCRIPTION:Trauma lives in the bodyŌĆōin our sensations\, gestures\, mov
 ements\, and in our capacity to feel and imagine. Trauma narrows our abil
 ity to express\, to feel alive\, and to dream. Words alone are not enough
  to fully capture or transform these embodied experiences.  Somatics and 
 art-based approaches offer a unique pathway in therapy. Integrating movem
 ent\, drawing\, creative writing\, and other holistic approaches provide 
 an invitation to express ourselves through the language of the body\, and
  give shape to what lies beneath the surface. Through creative exploratio
 n\, participants learn to recognize and release held patterns\, engage im
 agination as a resource\, and rebuild connections with themselves and oth
 ers.  This workshop is for practitioners seeking to incorporate body-base
 d and creative tools into their practice\, as well as those longing to re
 connect with their bodies\, creativity\, and sense of possibility. Partic
 ipants will leave the training with creative explorations to learn\, reco
 gnize\, and release held patterns\, engage imagination as a resource\, an
 d rebuild connection with self and others.  Instructor Dr. Sammartino wil
 l draw upon her twenty-year experience as a Somatic Movement therapist an
 d educator\, including her recent research-based work that explores the v
 alue of combined somatic and artistic approaches for trauma healing.Parti
 cipants in this workshop will:Explore how trauma lives in the body\, and 
 how arts and movement can support release\, regulation\, and renewal    C
 onnect with the creative body as a resource for resilience\, discovering 
 new possibilities for expression and healing    Engage in guided individu
 al explorations and group processes that foster connection and creativity
       This workshop will explore a variety of somatic and expressive art 
 methods. Please plan to bring your own pillows\, yoga mats\, blankets\, e
 tc. for participation. We also recommend wearing comfortable clothing for
  a variety of movement\, including sitting on the floor or in a chair.Det
 ails &amp\; RegistrationDate and Time: Friday\, April 10\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-
 4 p.m. &#160\;Instructor: Rosario Sammartino\, PhD\, RSME\, RSMTLocation:
  Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, Portland\, OregonCost and Credits: 
 $165\, includes 6 CEUs. GSEC Alumni\, Adjuncts\, and GSEC Clinical Mental
  Health Supervisors save 20%.&#160\;This workshop is currently full. Add 
 your name to the waitlist to be notified if space becomes available.Join 
 the Waitlist (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735424/?epid=a1aUY0000026JI9)A
 ccessibility: We are committed to making our events accessible to all nee
 ds and abilities. When registering\, please let us know your access needs
 . Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu)&#1
 60\;with questions.Please note: Discounted &#x2018\;Student Rate&#x2019\;
  registrations are for current students only and do not include continuin
 g education credit (CEU/PDUs)About the InstructorRosario Sammartino PhD\,
  RSME\, RSMT is a leading therapist and educator in the intersecting ’¼üe
 lds of Healing Arts\, Somatics and Depth Psychology. With over twenty yea
 rs of experience\, her work explores the relationship between body\, emot
 ion and imagination. Rosario is a core faculty member of Tamalpa Institut
 e\, the internationally recognized training center for movement-based exp
 ressive arts therapy\, where she trains an international student body. Sh
 e is an adjunct professor at Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\; as well
  as the founder of Anthropos Institute\, an art and self-development Cent
 er located in Buenos Aires\, Argentina\, where she is originally from. Ro
 sario leads numerous lectures &amp\; workshops nationally and internation
 ally. She has taken her work to healing and educational centers\, bringin
 g innovative models for health and embodied creativity to diverse populat
 ions.&#160\;New workshops and trainings are added to our calendar regular
 ly. For the latest on professional development related to your specific i
 nterests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/473
 5441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Trauma lives
  in the bodyŌĆōin our sensations\, gestures\, movements\, and in our capa
 city to feel and imagine. Trauma narrows our ability to express\, to feel
  alive\, and to dream. Words alone are not enough to fully capture or tra
 nsform these embodied experiences.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Som
 atics and art-based approaches offer a unique pathway in therapy. Integra
 ting movement\, drawing\, creative writing\, and other holistic approache
 s provide an invitation to express ourselves through the language of the 
 body\, and give shape to what lies beneath the surface. Through creative 
 exploration\, participants learn to recognize and release held patterns\,
  engage imagination as a resource\, and rebuild connections with themselv
 es and others.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This workshop is for pr
 actitioners seeking to incorporate body-based and creative tools into the
 ir practice\, as well as those longing to reconnect with their bodies\, c
 reativity\, and sense of possibility. Participants will leave the trainin
 g with creative explorations to learn\, recognize\, and release held patt
 erns\, engage imagination as a resource\, and rebuild connection with sel
 f and others.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Instructor Dr. Sammartin
 o will draw upon her twenty-year experience as a Somatic Movement therapi
 st and educator\, including her recent research-based work that explores 
 the value of combined somatic and artistic approaches for trauma healing.
 </p><p><strong>Participants in this workshop will:</strong></p><ul><li><p
  style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Explore</strong> how trauma lives in 
