DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260411T100000
LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Nutrition (Online)
DESCRIPTION:This course will include an overview of nutrition principles\
 , nutrition therapy\, and the role of the dietitian/nutritionist on the t
 reatment team\, and will be taught from a Health at Every Size (HAES) per
 spective.  Students will learn principles of nutritional rehabilitation f
 or malnourished and underweight clients\; structured eating and other int
 erventions for all eating disordered clients will be explored. Functions 
 of Anorexia Nervosa and other eating disorders will be discussed from a n
 utrition perspective\, and the cycle of restriction and bingeing will be 
 discussed with Bulimia Nervosa and Binge Eating Disorder.  Students will 
 also explore the principles of intuitive eating and mindful eating\, and 
 when these approaches are useful. Orthorexia will be covered in the conte
 xt of our obsessive diet culture\, along with ways to challenge these bel
 iefs.  Students will also learn strategies for working with families\, pa
 rticularly those of teens. Students will examine their own relationships 
 with food and explore strategies for making positive changes\, and will l
 earn how to establish professional boundaries around food issues with cli
 ents. Material will cover the collaboration between the dietitian/nutriti
 onist and therapist\, including case examples to illustrate and different
 iate roles of therapist and nutritionist.  This course is part of our Eat
 ing Disorders Certificate Program (https://graduate.lclark.edu/programs/c
 ontinuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/).Details &amp\; Regist
 rationDates and Time: Saturdays\, April 11\, 18\, and Sunday\, April 19\,
  2026\, 9 a.m.- 2:30 p.m.Instructor: Mikalah Barem\, MS\, RDNGraduate Con
 tinuing Education credit (current students and certificate candidates): C
 ECP 836-02\, 1 semester hour\, $375.&#160\;Register Online. Contact ccece
 rts@lclark.edu (mailto:ccecerts@lclark.edu) with questions.Individual Cla
 ss: We welcome students seeking to take individual courses within the cer
 tificate program for continuing education credit. Admission to the progra
 m is required. Click here for more information (https://graduate.lclark.e
 du/programs/continuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/#Admission
 )About the InstructorMikalah Barem\, MS\, RDN (she/her) is a Registered D
 ietitian in Oregon and Washington. She works at Nutrition Studio in Portl
 and and specializes in working with adults and adolescents with eating di
 sorders\, disordered eating\, and individuals looking to improve their re
 lationship with food and body who also need nutrition support for medical
  conditions. Mikalah is a member of the Columbia River Eating Disorder Ne
 twork.  Mikalah received a Bachelor of Science in Nutrition and Exercise 
 Physiology from Washington State University in 2019 as well as a Master o
 f Science in Dietetics from Washington State University in 2021. Prior to
  working at Nutrition Studio\, Mikalah worked in PHP\, IOP and outpatient
  levels of care\, including launching and spending 3 years working in a s
 pecialized Binge Eating Disorder IOP program.  Mikalah is a Certified Int
 uitive Eating Counselor and loves bringing mindfulness and body-centered 
 somatic approaches to nutritional treatments for eating disorders when po
 ssible. She is committed to weight-inclusive care\, fat liberation\, and 
 uses the Health at Every Size framework in her work.New workshops and tra
 inings are added to our calendar regularly. For the latest on professiona
 l development related to your specific interests\, sign up for our mailin
 g list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This course 
 will include an overview of nutrition principles\, nutrition therapy\, an
 d the role of the dietitian/nutritionist on the treatment team\, and will
  be taught from a Health at Every Size (HAES) perspective.</p><p style="l
 ine-height: 1.5\;">  Students will learn principles of nutritional rehabi
 litation for malnourished and underweight clients\; structured eating and
  other interventions for all eating disordered clients will be explored. 
 Functions of Anorexia Nervosa and other eating disorders will be discusse
 d from a nutrition perspective\, and the cycle of restriction and bingein
 g will be discussed with Bulimia Nervosa and Binge Eating Disorder.</p><p
  style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Students will also explore the principles o
 f intuitive eating and mindful eating\, and when these approaches are use
 ful. Orthorexia will be covered in the context of our obsessive diet cult
 ure\, along with ways to challenge these beliefs.</p><p style="line-heigh
 t: 1.5\;">  Students will also learn strategies for working with families
 \, particularly those of teens. Students will examine their own relations
 hips with food and explore strategies for making positive changes\, and w
 ill learn how to establish professional boundaries around food issues wit
 h clients. Material will cover the collaboration between the dietitian/nu
 tritionist and therapist\, including case examples to illustrate and diff
 erentiate roles of therapist and nutritionist.</p><p style="line-height: 
 1.5\;">  This course is part of our <a href="https://graduate.lclark.edu/
 programs/continuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/">Eating Diso
 rders Certificate Program</a>.</p><hr /><h2 style="line-height: 1.5\;"><s
 trong>Details &amp\; Registration</strong></h2><p style="line-height: 1.6
 \;"><strong>Dates and Time:</strong> Saturdays\, April 11\, 18\, and Sund
 ay\, April 19\, 2026\, 9 a.m.- 2:30 p.m.</p><p style="line-height: 1.6\;"
 ><strong>Instructor:</strong> Mikalah Barem\, MS\, RDN</p><p style="line-
 height: 1.6\;"><strong>Graduate Continuing Education credit <em>(current 
 students and certificate candidates)</em>:</strong> CECP 836-02\, 1 semes
 ter hour\, $375.&#160\;<a href="https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735425"><str
 ong>Register Online</strong></a>. Contact <a href="mailto:ccecerts@lclark
 .edu">ccecerts@lclark.edu</a> with questions.</p><p style="line-height: 1
 .6\;"><strong>Individual Class:</strong> We welcome students seeking to t
 ake individual courses within the certificate program for continuing educ
 ation credit. Admission to the program is required. <strong><a href="http
 s://graduate.lclark.edu/programs/continuing_education/certificates/eating
 _disorders/#Admission">Click here for more information</a></strong></p><h
