 e second Wednesday of every month\, February-May.</p><p><strong>About the
  Lecture</strong></p><p data-path-to-node="3">  Professor Beckham present
 s <strong data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="35">"The Pig War: San
  Juan Islands in Conflict\, 1859ŌĆō1872\,"</strong> a lecture detailing t
 he international controversy in Puget Sound that nearly brought the Unite
 d States and Great Britain to war. This historical event resonates with m
 odern tensions regarding the 49th parallel boundary\, tariffs\, and sover
 eign rights.</p><p data-path-to-node="4">  Prof. Beckham examines how the
  killing of a pig on San Juan Island precipitated an outrageous explosion
  of conflict over the exact location of the boundary between Canada and t
 he United States. The "Pig War" led to a significant build-up of army and
  navy forces and the construction of fortifications\, with tensions only 
 ultimately resolved through international arbitration by Kaiser Wilhelm I
  of Germany.</p><p data-path-to-node="5">  Using historical photographs\,
  watercolors\, and maps\, Prof. Beckham places the San Juan Islands confl
 ict within the broader context of the American Civil War\, boundary dispu
 tes in the <strong data-path-to-node="5" data-index-in-node="183">Stikine
  River</strong> watershed\, fisheries off the coast of Nova Scotia\, and 
 American claims against England regarding the sinking of Union vessels by
  the British-built\, Confederate-operated <strong data-path-to-node="5" d
 ata-index-in-node="366">CSS Alabama</strong>.</p><p><strong>About the Pre
 senter</strong></p><p data-path-to-node="1"><strong data-path-to-node="1"
  data-index-in-node="0">Stephen Dow Beckham</strong> is Pamplin Professor
  Emeritus of History at Lewis &amp\; Clark College\, where he served for 
 forty-two years. A preeminent authority on the American West and the Lewi
 s &amp\; Clark Expedition\, Professor Beckham dedicated the majority of h
 is career to teaching undergraduate students in the College of Arts and S
 ciences\, while also contributing his expertise to the Law School's India
 n Law Program.</p><p data-path-to-node="2">  Renowned for his immersive t
 eaching\, he famously led field-based courses retracing the Lewis &amp\; 
 Clark trail on horseback and sailing the Northwest Coast. Beyond the clas
 sroom\, he has served as an expert witness in over forty tribal rights ca
 ses and currently chairs the Oregon Committee on Historic Preservation. A
  former Oregon Professor of the Year and recipient of the American Histor
 ical Association's Asher Distinguished Teaching Award\, Professor Beckham
  also serves on the board of the Theodore Roosevelt Presidential Library\
 , continuing his lifelong commitment to historical scholarship and conser
 vation.</p><p style="text-align: center\;">  &#160\;</p>
