DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260517
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260518
LOCATION:Menucha Retreat and Conference Center\, 38711 E\, Historic Colum
 bia River Hwy\, Corbett\, OR
SUMMARY:Liberatory Leadership: Embracing Grief and Possibility While Buil
 ding Beloved Community (In-Person)
DESCRIPTION:This Courage to Lead┬« retreat is designed to help participan
 ts renew their passion\, enthusiasm\, and commitment to themselves and th
 e communities they serve\, and is open to those identifying as women who 
 are in leadershipŌĆöwhether formally or informally.  This four-day offeri
 ng is for those seeking to hold and respond to the complexity of our time
 \, while finding rest and rejuvenation through practicing community toget
 her. We will meet during the fullness of spring when the abundance of lig
 ht and energy invites us to remember all that brought us to this moment. 
  As individuals and as leaders\, we can expand our capacity to be fully p
 resent to ourselves and our community\, and reclaim our power to meet our
  calling in these increasingly challenging times.&#160\;With courage\, co
 mpassion and creativity we will share practices to hold our current reali
 ties\, wherever we find ourselves.We will invite the beauty of this speci
 al land above the Columbia Gorge to be a teacher and guide.&#160\;Togethe
 r we willŌĆ”Pause\, breathe\, embrace silence\, and disconnect from techn
 ology and our demanding pace of life  Reduce isolation and build communit
 ies of care that provide support in hard times\, and act as containers fo
 r liberatory innovations  Identify reflective practices that help us embr
 ace grief and build hope for the future of our communities  Deepen our sk
 ills to ask open-ended questions that help us and other to uncover inner 
 wisdom  Expand capacity to be fully present to ourselves and others in wa
 ys that affirm and heal  Strengthen our ability to hold paradox\, moving 
 beyond either-or thinking into holding opposing truths and complexity  Le
 arn and participate in a Clearness Committee (https://couragerenewal.org/
 library/the-clearness-committee-a-communal-approach-to-discernment/)\, de
 signed after a powerful problem-solving model from the 1600's    We are e
 xcited to have you join in retreat\, grounded in the Courage &amp\; Renew
 al┬« approach\, upon which Circles of Trust (http://couragerenewal.org/ap
 proach/)┬« is based\, designed to build a trustworthy space for telling o
 ur truths and listening to the truths of others.Retreat Details &amp\;&#1
 60\;RegistrationDate and Time: Sunday-Wednesday\, May 17-20\, 2026. The r
 etreat will begin at 4 p.m. Sunday and conclude at 11 a.m. on Wednesday.L
 ocation: Menucha Retreat and Conference Center\, Corbett\, ORFacilitators
 : Anita Garcia Morales\; Dawn Montgomery\, EdD\; and Jen Wagley\, MEd\, M
 DivCost: Registration fees include three nights of lodging\, 9 meals (beg
 inning Sunday dinner and ending Wednesday Breakfast)\, and all supplies\,
  snacks\, beverages\, and 18 PDUs or CEUs.Single Occupancy Room: $1\,195 
 (Join the Waitlist) (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735424/?epid=a1aUY00000
 23cE5)Shared Occupancy: $895  Register Online (https://lclark.tfaforms.ne
 t/4735427/?epid=a1aUY0000023cE5)Accessibility:We are committed to making 
 our events accessible to all needs and abilities. When registering\, plea
 se let us know your access needs. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclar
 k.edu with questions.Scholarship Fund: We strive to keep our Courage retr
 eats accessible to all who wish to participate. Please consider making a 
 tax-deductible donation (https://engage.lclark.edu/register/gsecgiving?sy
 s:gift:fund=4dfb9f4e-7351-4d84-91fe-531631c248c7&amp\;sys:gift:notes=Cour
 age%20and%20Renewal%20Retreats%20Scholarship%20Fund) to our scholarship f
 und.About the FacilitatorsAnita Garcia Morales retired from Seattle Publi
 c Schools after 35 years of teaching and learning from students\, coachin
 g/mentoring educators\, and designing and facilitating DEIB sessions for 
 all district employees. Through 'Racing to Equity'\, a consulting group A
 nita co-founded and co-owns\, she facilitates anti-bias circles with comm
 unity groups\, government agencies\, students\, educators and works with 
 immigrant families who are just learning to navigate the complexities of 
 their newly adopted home. Anita is a Courage &amp\; Renewal Facilitator\,
  a Positive Discipline Certified Associate\, and a Class Action Certified
  Trainer. The common thread that runs through all that Anita does is her 
 focus on social justice and equity. Anita is on a journey of self-healing
  from the generational trauma that she\, like IBPOC across the country\, 
 have inherited and continue to experience. Anita also sees herself as a h
 ealer calling up her ancestral gifts and gathers circles of folx on simil
 ar paths of healing and liberation. In this work\, IBPOC center themselve
 s in their quest to show up in the world more authentically and unapologe
 tically.Dawn Montgomery\, EdD is a change facilitator and insightful thou
 ght partner. She supports leaders from a wide variety of fields\, includi
 ng educators\, nonprofit executives\, and community administrators as the
 y find their way in challenging times. Assisting humans in their discover
 y and reconnection to their deepest longings has been a passion for many 
 years. Her background in K-12 and college education as teacher\, principa
 l\, and district leader support her coaching practice and team facilitati
 on. She believes transformation is born when a circle of humans sit toget
 her to listen\, to speak their deepest truths and to share their wildest 
 imaginations for the world. She is expert at holding space for both indiv
 idual leaders and teams as an executive coach\, conflict mediator\, equit
 y-focused professional developer and a certified Courage &amp\; Renewal f
 acilitator. She is committed to making a difference in the lives of indiv
 iduals and their communities.Jen Wagley\, MEd\, M Div serves as Deputy Di
 rector of Houston in Action. She formerly served as the founding Executiv
 e Director of Our Children Oregon\, an advocacy and research organization
  committed to improving child well-being. She brings two decades of exper
 ience in organizational leadership\, grass-roots power building and compr
 ehensive community development and engagement. Jenifer is a facilitator w
 ith the Center for Courage &amp\; Renewal. Her work with the Center has b
 een key to her sustainability as a leader and has provided her the opport
 unity of supporting other leaders across the country. Previously she serv
 ed as the Deputy Director of Avenue Community Development Corporation in 
 Houston\, TX. Jenifer is driven by a passion to create a more just\, heal
 thy\, loving society where every person/being has what they need to thriv
 e. Jen is mom to three boys and loves to hike\, coach basketball and buil
 d friendships. Jenifer holds two master's degrees from Baylor University 
 and Truett Seminary.&#160\;New workshops and trainings are added to our c
 alendar regularly. For the latest on professional development related to 
 your specific interests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https://lclark.t
 faforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This Courage
  to Lead┬« retreat is designed to help participants renew their passion\,
  enthusiasm\, and commitment to themselves and the communities they serve
 \, and is open to those identifying as women who are in leadershipŌĆöwhet
 her formally or informally.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This four-
 day offering is for those seeking to hold and respond to the complexity o
 f our time\, while finding rest and rejuvenation through practicing commu
 nity together. We will meet during the fullness of spring when the abunda
 nce of light and energy invites us to remember all that brought us to thi
 s moment.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  As individuals and as leader
 s\, we can expand our capacity to be fully present to ourselves and our c
 ommunity\, and reclaim our power to meet our calling in these increasingl
 y challenging times.<span class="s2">&#160\;With courage\, compassion and
  creativity we will share practices to hold our current realities\, where
 ver we find ourselves.</span></p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><span clas
 s="s1">We will invite the beauty of this special land above the Columbia 
 Gorge to be a teacher and guide.</span>&#160\;</p><p><strong>Together we 
 willŌĆ”</strong></p><ul><li style="line-height: 1.5\;">Pause\, breathe\, 
 embrace silence\, and disconnect from technology and our demanding pace o
 f life  </li><li style="line-height: 1.5\;">Reduce isolation and build co
 mmunities of care that provide support in hard times\, and act as contain
 ers for liberatory innovations  </li><li style="line-height: 1.5\;">Ident
 ify reflective practices that help us embrace grief and build hope for th
 e future of our communities  </li><li style="line-height: 1.5\;">Deepen o
 ur skills to ask open-ended questions that help us and other to uncover i
 nner wisdom  </li><li style="line-height: 1.5\;">Expand capacity to be fu
 lly present to ourselves and others in ways that affirm and heal  </li><l
 i style="line-height: 1.5\;">Strengthen our ability to hold paradox\, mov
 ing beyond either-or thinking into holding opposing truths and complexity
   </li><li style="line-height: 1.5\;">Learn and participate in a <a href=
 "https://couragerenewal.org/library/the-clearness-committee-a-communal-ap
 proach-to-discernment/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Clearness Committe
 e</a>\, designed after a powerful problem-solving model from the 1600's  
 </li></ul><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  We are excited to have you join
  in retreat\, grounded in the Courage &amp\; Renewal┬« approach\, upon wh
 ich <a href="http://couragerenewal.org/approach/">Circles of Trust</a>┬« 
 is based\, designed to build a trustworthy space for telling our truths a
 nd listening to the truths of others.</p><hr /><h2><strong>Retreat Detail
 s &amp\;&#160\;</strong><strong>Registration</strong></h2><p style="line-
 height: 1.5\;"><strong>Date and Time:</strong> Sunday-Wednesday\, May 17-
 20\, 2026. The retreat will begin at 4 p.m. Sunday and conclude at 11 a.m
 . on Wednesday.</p><p><strong>Location:</strong> Menucha Retreat and Conf
 erence Center\, Corbett\, OR</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Fac
 ilitators:</strong> Anita Garcia Morales\; Dawn Montgomery\, EdD\; and Je
 n Wagley\, MEd\, MDiv</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Cost:</str
 ong> Registration fees include three nights of lodging\, 9 meals (beginni
 ng Sunday dinner and ending Wednesday Breakfast)\, and all supplies\, sna
 cks\, beverages\, and 18 PDUs or CEUs.</p><ul><li><strong>Single Occupanc
 y Room:</strong> $1\,195 <a href="https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735424/?ep
 id=a1aUY0000023cE5" target="_blank" rel="noopener">(Join the Waitlist)</a
 ></li><li><strong>Shared Occupancy:</strong> $895  </li></ul><p style="li
 ne-height: 1.5\;"><strong style="background-color: transparent\;"><a clas
 s="btn-small-style-1" href="https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735427/?epid=a1a
 UY0000023cE5">Register Online</a></strong></p><p style="line-height: 1.5\
 ;"><strong style="background-color: transparent\;">Accessibility:</strong
 ><span style="background-color: transparent\;">We are committed to making
  our events accessible to all needs and abilities. When registering\, ple
 ase let us know your access needs. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lcla
 rk.edu with questions</span><span style="font-weight: 400\;">.</span></p>
 <p style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Scholarship Fund:</strong> We striv
 e to keep our Courage retreats accessible to all who wish to participate.
  Please consider making a <a href="https://engage.lclark.edu/register/gse
 cgiving?sys:gift:fund=4dfb9f4e-7351-4d84-91fe-531631c248c7&amp\;sys:gift:
 notes=Courage%20and%20Renewal%20Retreats%20Scholarship%20Fund">tax-deduct
 ible donation</a> to our scholarship fund.</p><hr /><h2><strong>About the
