LOCATION:Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School
SUMMARY:Trans Form: Grounding into Trans History\, Liberation\, and Hope 
 (In-Person)
DESCRIPTION:At TransActive (https://graduate.lclark.edu/programs/continui
 ng_education/transactive/) we are working to strengthen the systems that 
 surround trans and gender diverse youth. This workshop will help particip
 ants to build a clear understanding of the current political climate we a
 re experiencing\, and discuss how we can leverage effective communication
 \, liberatory practices\, and community engagement to support trans lives
  in this moment.During the workshop participants will:Reflect on the hist
 ory of anti-trans legislation  Take a clear look at the past 10 years of 
 laws affecting transgender people\, both across the United States and her
 e in Oregon\, to better understand the broader context shaping people's l
 ives today.Practice effective communication  Learn strategies for talking
  about these topics with clients and families in ways that are clear\, re
 spectful\, and appropriate for different ages.Explore actionable liberato
 ry practices  Discuss what liberation looks like in action\, bringing tog
 ether social change research with examples of practice established by tra
 nsgender leaders.Map our communities  Create maps of our own communities 
 and explore opportunities to practice community\, leverage change\, and s
 trengthen connections with our people and our values.Following the worksh
 op\, participants will be able to:Explain the social-political processes 
 that have resulted in increased political targeting of transgender and ge
 nder nonconforming communities  Speak to the local political landscape an
 d current protections and challenges in Oregon for transgender communitie
 s  Identify and explain personal hope practice  Understand one to three l
 everage points for enacting change can be utilized to support transgender
  communities in the current political climate    This training is for any
 one supporting trans and gender-diverse youthŌĆöincluding educators\, the
 rapists\, health care providers\, organizers\, parents\, and caregiversŌĆ
 öand is designed to deepen understanding of our current moment while embe
 dding liberatory\, trans-centered practices into daily life and work.  Th
 is workshop may meet the OBLPCT Cultural Competence Continuing Education 
 requirement. Click here for more information (http://www.oregon.gov/oblpc
 t/Pages/CCCE.aspx)Event DetailsDate and Time: Saturday\, May 30\, 2026\, 
 9 a.m-4 p.m.Location: Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, South ChapelIn
 structors: Carson Varnum\, MEd\, and Finn Johnson&#160\;RegistrationCommu
 nity &amp\; Graduate Student Rate: $60 (no CEUs or PDUs)CEU/PDU Registrat
 ion: $140\, includes 6 CEUs or PDUs\, GSEC Alumni and Adjuncts save 20%Cu
 rrent GSEC Supervisors: $112\, includes 6 CEUs or PDUs  Limited no-cost r
 egistrations available for GSEC Faculty and Staff.Email cce@lclark.edu (m
 ailto:cce@lclark.edu) to register.Register Online (https://lclark.tfaform
 s.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY000002P22H)Workshop registration ends May 24\, 20
 26Accessibility: We are committed to making our events accessible to all 
 needs and abilities. When registering\, please let us know your access ne
 eds. Contact us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu)
 &#160\;with questions.Please note: Discounted &#x2018\;Student Rate&#x201
 9\; registrations are for current students only and do not include contin
 uing education credit (CEU/PDUs)About the InstructorsCarson Varnum\, MEd\
 , (he/him) is a community builder and educator with an expertise in sexua
 l health\, sexualities\, peer education\, and community development. Cars
 on specializes in building capacity in sex educators\, creating sexuality
  education and leadership development programming for adolescents\, and d
 eveloping programs that center Queer and Trans communities. Carson works 
 at Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School as TransActives's Head of Education
  and Outreach\, where he supports transgender\, non-binary\, and other ge
 nder expansive youth by strengthening the systems that surround them. He 
 received his Masters of Education in Human Sexuality from Widener Univers
 ity in 2012 and is currently a PhD student in Education and Leadership at
  Pacific University. Carson is a big fan of being on mountains\, in river
 s\, and with friends.&#160\;Finn Johnson (he/him) is a PhD Candidate in W
 omen\, Gender\, and Sexuality Studies and Ethnic Studies at Oregon State 
 University\, and a law student at Lewis &amp\; Clark Law School. He holds
  an MA in Women\, Gender\, and Sexuality Studies from Oregon State and a 
 BA in Sexuality\, Gender\, and Queer Studies from Portland State Universi
 ty. Before law school\, Finn taught and developed undergraduate courses i
 n Women\, Gender\, and Sexuality Studies at Oregon State\, focusing on qu
 eer and trans studies. He also publishes scholarship in Critical Race The
 ory\, Critical Legal Studies\, and LGBTQIA+ STEM Studies. His doctoral re
 search has examined anti-transgender legislation in the U.S. since 2016. 
 Beyond research\, he has extensive experience as an activist\, lobbyist\,
  and community educator in LGBTQIA+ and reproductive justice policy.New w
 orkshops and trainings are added to our calendar regularly. For the lates
 t on professional development related to your specific interests\, sign u
 p for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  At <a href="
 https://graduate.lclark.edu/programs/continuing_education/transactive/" t
 arget="_blank" rel="noopener">TransActive</a> we are working to strengthe
 n the systems that surround trans and gender diverse youth. This workshop
  will help participants to build a clear understanding of the current pol
 itical climate we are experiencing\, and discuss how we can leverage effe
 ctive communication\, liberatory practices\, and community engagement to 
 support trans lives in this moment.</p><h3 style="line-height: 1.5\;"><st
 rong>During the workshop participants will:</strong></h3><h4 style="line-
 height: 1.5\;"><strong>Reflect on the history of anti-trans legislation</
 strong></h4><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Take a clear look at the past
  10 years of laws affecting transgender people\, both across the United S
 tates and here in Oregon\, to better understand the broader context shapi
 ng people's lives today.</p><h4 style="line-height: 1.5\;"><strong>Practi
 ce effective communication</strong></h4><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  L
 earn strategies for talking about these topics with clients and families 
