LOCATION:Virtual\, and Clackamas Education Service District
SUMMARY:Healthy Cross Cultural Teams - Pre K-12 (Hybrid)
DESCRIPTION:Educators need systematic ways to engage each other on how cu
 lture and race shape all aspects of their workŌĆöfrom curriculum and inst
 ruction to assessment\, feedback\, family and community relationships\, a
 nd cross-cultural collaboration with colleagues.  This week-long course f
 or school-based Pre K-12 educators will help individuals and teams examin
 e their positionality and racial socialization through critical reflectio
 n.  Participants will explore how racial identity development and cultura
 l literacy strengthen relationships with colleagues\, students\, and comm
 unities\, and together build skills for disrupting inequitable systems th
 rough cross-cultural solidarity.Participants in this course will strength
 en their skills around:      Understanding how our racial identity impact
 s our work in schools and the role of racial literacy in creating healthy
  identity development          Developing processes to nurture and grow p
 rincipled relationships across race          Sustaining cross-racial soli
 darity while navigating institutional realities and resistance    Action 
 planning to create a vision and values to help guide the work of cross-ra
 cial teams\, and develop next steps to continue the work back at their si
 tes  Course DetailsDates and Times: Monday-Friday\, June 22-26\, 2026In-P
 erson: June 22\, 24\, 26\, 2026\, 9 a.m.- 4 p.m.\, Clackamas Education Se
 rvice District\, 13455 SE 97th Avenue\, Clackamas\, OR&#160\;Virtual:&#16
 0\;June 23\, 25\, 2026\, 9:30-11:30 a.m.Instructors: Elizabeth Denevi\, P
 hD\, and Jasmine LockeGraduate Continuing Education credit: CEED-866-21\,
  2 semester hours\, $770Limited scholarships available to educators worki
 ng in a Multnomah or Clackamas County School District\, MESD\, or CESD. A
 ll course texts and materials will be provided to all participants at no 
 cost.  Course RegistrationStep 1: Follow the link below to access registr
 ation and scholarship applicationStep 2: CCE will follow up by email with
  credit-bearing course registration and enrollment instructionsRegister o
 nline (https://pdnetworks.soesd.k12.or.us/public/events/view-event/15508)
 About the InstructorsElizabeth Denevi\, PhD\, is an assistant clinical pr
 ofessor at Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School of Education and Counseling
 . She has served as a classroom teacher as well as an equity director\, l
 eadership coach\, and director of professional development. She is co-aut
 hor Learning and Teaching While White: Antiracist Strategies for School C
 ommunities (with Jenna Chandler Ward)&#160\;as well as Integrating Educat
 or Well-Being\, Growth\, and Evaluation: Four Foundations for Leaders (wi
 th Lori Cohen)\, both featured titles in Routledge's Equity and Social Ju
 stice in Education series.Jasmine Locke is an equity-centered educational
  leader and doctoral candidate at Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School of E
 ducation and Counseling. Her research explores racial literacy\, socializ
 ation\, and the educational trajectories of students engaged in Black Stu
 dent Unions. With a decade of experience as a classroom teacher\, school 
 support specialist and equity coach\, she brings deep expertise in cultur
 ally responsive pedagogy\, student identity development\, and systems-lev
 el change. She is featured in Teach for Climate Justice: A Vision for Tra
 nsforming Education\, highlighting her commitment to joy as a form of res
 istance.New workshops and trainings are added to our calendar regularly. 
 For the latest on professional development related to your specific inter
 ests\, sign up for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441
 )
