LOCATION:Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, South Chapel and York 107
SUMMARY:Applied Suicide Intervention Skills Training (ASIST) [In-Person]
DESCRIPTION:The Applied Suicide Intervention Skills Training (ASIST) is a
 n intensive\, interactive and practice-dominated course for those who wan
 t to feel more comfortable\, confident and competent in providing an inte
 rvention with someone who is having thoughts of suicide.&#160\;This works
 hop will provide extensive opportunities for supported skills practice an
 d shared participant experiences that enrich learning.After this workshop
 \, participants will have an increased ability to:      Recognize when so
 meone may be thinking about suicide          Provide a skilled interventi
 on\, including connect the person to further support          Guide the d
 evelopment of a safety plan through a collaborative\, helping relationshi
 p          Consider how personal and community attitudes about suicide af
 fect someone's openness to seek help and the caregiver's ability to provi
 de it          Reduce suicide stigma and build confidence and capacity to
  provide suicide first aidWho should attend? The training is for anyone i
 n a position of trust\, including mental health and addictions profession
 als\, school psychologists\, school counselors\, educators\, healthcare w
 orkers\, peer support and recovery specialists\, housing specialists\, la
 w enforcement\, faith leaders\, and community volunteers.  "Prior to part
 icipating in ASIST\, I was reluctant to get involved in conversations inv
 olving suicide because I felt uneasy about how to engage effectively. I w
 alked away from this training with clear and applicable tools to enter a 
 conversation with confidence and fearlessness\, equipped to support and c
 onverse openly about suicide. It was absolutely one of the most valuable 
 trainings I have experienced in my career."  - Counselor\, Roosevelt High
  SchoolTraining credits are NASP and NASW-approved for Continuing Profess
 ional Development (CPD).Details &amp\; RegistrationDates and Time: Friday
  &amp\; Saturday\, June 26-27\, 2026\, 8:30 a.m.-4:30 p.m.&#160\;Location
 : Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School\, South Chapel and York 107Instructo
 rs: Leslie Rodgers\, and Kathy Wilson-FeyCost and Credits: $325\, include
 s 15 NASP-Approved CEUs or PDUs (12.75 NASW Credits). Alumni\, Adjuncts\,
  and GSEC Clinical Mental Health Supervisors save 20%.&#160\;Register Onl
 ine (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY000002Unrl)Accessibili
 ty: We are committed to making our events accessible to all needs and abi
 lities. When registering\, please let us know your access needs. Contact 
 us at 503-768-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu)&#160\;with q
 uestions.Please note: Discounted &#x2018\;Student Rate&#x2019\; registrat
 ions are for current students only and do not include continuing educatio
 n credit (CEU/PDUs)About the InstructorsLeslie Rodgers is a licensed clin
 ical social worker and registered ASIST (Applied Suicide Intervention Ski
 lls) trainer with over 20 years experience working with children and adul
 ts in various therapeutic settings\, including group homes\, psychiatric 
 hospitals\, and schools. Her current work has involved implementing best 
 practice procedures and providing staff development in student threat ass
 essment\, suicide prevention\, and crisis response for school districts. 
 She holds a BA from the University of Texas and a Masters in Social Work 
 from Portland State University.Kathy Wilson-Fey is a registered ASIST Tra
 iner and has clinical therapy and teaching experience in a variety of set
 tings\, including community college\, community mental health\, and an in
 ternational university. She has 15 years of experience as a mental health
  specialist in public schools\, where she worked with students and famili
 es\, trained school staff on suicide intervention\, and coordinated schoo
 l support during crises. Kathy is fluent in Spanish and is committed to e
 quity work and cultural competence. She holds a BA from Whitman College a
 nd a Masters in Counseling Psychology from the University of Oregon.New w
 orkshops and trainings are added to our calendar regularly. For the lates
 t on professional development related to your specific interests\, sign u
 p for our mailing list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
