DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260627T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260627T173000
LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Body Politics (Online)
DESCRIPTION:As clinicians\, we need to be prepared to help clients decons
 truct how their bodies have been storied.  This includes raising awarenes
 s of\, and challenging\, the impact of societal and relational power dyna
 mics. These dynamics impact not only our inner dialog\, but the everyday 
 realities of our lives.  This course explores how we evaluate our bodies 
 through the lens of "unidentified others\," as well as the lived experien
 ce and consequences of looks\, privilege and discrimination.  Participant
 s will consider liberation-based counseling practices to counter the obje
 ctification\, commodification\, power and gendering of bodies in late cap
 italist societies.  The focus of this course is to raise awareness of bod
 y politics in the clinical practice and creating opportunities for change
  through individual and relational wellbeing.  This course is part of our
  Eating Disorders Certificate Program (https://graduate.lclark.edu/progra
 ms/continuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/).Course Details &a
 mp\; RegistrationDates and Times: Saturday-Sunday\, June 27-28\, 2026\, 9
  a.m.-3:50 p.m.\, PT\, OnlineInstructor:&#160\;Krystal Marcinkiewicz\, MA
 \, LPC\, LMHCCurrent Students and Certificate Candidates: CECP 837-1\, 1 
 semester hour of Graduate Continuing Education credit\, $385.&#160\;Indiv
 idual Class: We welcome students seeking to take individual courses withi
 n the certificate program. Admission to the program is required. Click he
 re for more information (https://www.lclark.edu/programs/continuing_educa
 tion/certificates/eating_disorders/#Admission)Register Online (https://lc
 lark.tfaforms.net/4735425)We are committed to making our events accessibl
 e to all needs and abilities. If you have a disability that may impact yo
 ur academic performance\, you may request accommodations by meeting with 
 the Office of Student Accessibility staff and submitting documentation on
  the Office of Student Accessibility website (/offices/student-accessibil
 ity/). Please be aware that the process for evaluation and implementation
  of accommodations could take 2-3 weeks\, so please be in touch with the 
 OSA as soon as possible. Email access@lclark.edu (mailto:access@lclark.ed
 u) with any additional questions or concerns.About the Instructor Krystal
  Marcinkiewicz\, MA\, LPC\, LMHC is a Licensed Professional Counselor and
  Clinical Supervisor\, having earned her Masters Degree in Professional M
 ental Health Counseling from Lewis &amp\; Clark College in 2018. Drawing 
 from an integrative feminist approach\, her work is grounded in person-ce
 ntered values\, emphasizing authentic connection\, and collaborative enga
 gement. Her primary clinical focus is supporting clients in navigating id
 entity development\, body politics\, neurodivergence\, emotional codepend
 ency\, highly sensitive personalities and other complex emotional experie
 nces.  In addition to clinical work\, Krystal is also passionate in train
 ing and mentoring emerging counselors. She is an adjunct professor\, teac
 hing a wide variety of graduate counseling courses with an underlying emp
 hasis on counselor identity development\, reflective practice\, and culti
 vating professional resilience.  In both the classroom\, and her clinical
  work\, Krystal is committed to creating affirming spaces that honor inte
 rsectional identities and lived experience.New workshops and trainings ar
 e added to our calendar regularly. For the latest on professional develop
 ment related to your specific interests\, sign up for our mailing list! (
 https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  As clinician
 s\, we need to be prepared to help clients deconstruct how their bodies h
 ave been storied.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This includes raisin
 g awareness of\, and challenging\, the impact of societal and relational 
 power dynamics. These dynamics impact not only our inner dialog\, but the
  everyday realities of our lives.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This
  course explores how we evaluate our bodies through the lens of "unidenti
 fied others\," as well as the lived experience and consequences of looks\
 , privilege and discrimination.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Partic
 ipants will consider liberation-based counseling practices to counter the
  objectification\, commodification\, power and gendering of bodies in lat
 e capitalist societies.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  The focus of t
 his course is to raise awareness of body politics in the clinical practic
