DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260710T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260710T100000
LOCATION:Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate School
SUMMARY:Understanding\, Exploring\, and Supporting Perimenopause and Meno
 pause Experiences in The Therapy Room (In-Person)
DESCRIPTION:Menopause and perimenopause can magnify emotional and psychol
 ogical distressŌĆöoften showing up as irritability\, mood shifts\, anxiet
 y\, depression\, grief\, self-doubt\, brain fog\, and heightened emotiona
 l insecurity. These experiences can disrupt relationships\, work function
 ing\, and a client's sense of identity and self-efficacy. Many clients re
 port little preparation\, limited validation\, and inconsistent guidance 
 on what to expect or how to cope.  This skills-based training equips clin
 icians and helping professionals with practical\, trauma-informed\, and c
 ulturally responsive tools to support clients who are navigating menopaus
 e-related mental health and life-transition stress.  Presenter Audrianna 
 J. Gurr\, LPC\, CADCI\, mental health clinician and author of I'm Still H
 ot! Surviving and Thriving in Your Mental Health During Menopause\, will 
 guide participants through a framework for identifying common emotional p
 atterns\, normalizing the experience without minimizing it\, and selectin
 g concrete interventions that can be used immediately in session.Followin
 g this training\, participants will have the ability to:      Identify co
 mmon emotional and psychological experiences that may intensify during pe
 rimenopause/menopause and differentiate them from other clinical presenta
 tions          Apply a brief session-ready framework for validating menop
 ause-related distress while supporting client agency and self-compassion 
          Use the "Three Tiers" expectations tool to reduce anxiety-driven
  over-control and support realistic planning.&#160\;          Teach asser
 tiveness and boundary-setting skills using a "Personal Bill of Rights" le
 ns to strengthen self-advocacy and relational functioning.          Adapt
  interventions with attention to equity and diversity\, including how gen
 der socialization\, culture\, and systemic barriers shape help-seeking\, 
 access to care\, and empowerment during midlife transitions.    Details &
 amp\; RegistrationDate and Time: Friday\, July 10\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-12 p.m.
 Location: Lewis &amp\; Clark Graduate SchoolPresenter: Audrianna J. Gurr\
 , LPC\, CADCICost and Credits: $79\, includes 3 CEUs. GSEC Alumni\, Adjun
 cts\, and Clinical Mental Health Supervisors save 20%. $40 GSEC Student R
 ate.  Limited no-cost registration for GSEC Faculty and Staff. Contact cc
 e@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu) to register.Register Online (https:/
 /lclark.tfaforms.net/wf1W4MQ?epid=a1aUY000002Unjh)Accessibility: We are c
 ommitted to making our events accessible to all needs and abilities. When
  registering\, please let us know your access needs. Contact us at 503-76
 8-6040 or cce@lclark.edu (mailto:cce@lclark.edu)&#160\;with questions.Ple
 ase note: Discounted &#x2018\;Student Rate&#x2019\; registrations are for
  current students only and do not include continuing education credit (CE
 U/PDUs)About the InstructorInstructor bio coming soonNew workshops and tr
 ainings are added to our calendar regularly. For the latest on profession
 al development related to your specific interests\, sign up for our maili
 ng list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
