DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260711T090000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260711T173000
LOCATION:Online
SUMMARY:Body Politics (Online)
DESCRIPTION:As clinicians\, we need to be prepared to help clients decons
 truct how their bodies have been storied.  This includes raising awarenes
 s of\, and challenging\, the impact of societal and relational power dyna
 mics. These dynamics impact not only our inner dialog\, but the everyday 
 realities of our lives.  This course explores how we evaluate our bodies 
 through the lens of "unidentified others\," as well as the lived experien
 ce and consequences of looks\, privilege and discrimination.  Participant
 s will consider liberation-based counseling practices to counter the obje
 ctification\, commodification\, power and gendering of bodies in late cap
 italist societies.  The focus of this course is to raise awareness of bod
 y politics in the clinical practice and creating opportunities for change
  through individual and relational wellbeing.  This course is part of our
  Eating Disorders Certificate Program (https://graduate.lclark.edu/progra
 ms/continuing_education/certificates/eating_disorders/).Course Details &a
 mp\; RegistrationDates and Times: Saturday &amp\; Sunday\, July 11 &amp\;
  12\, 2026\, 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m.\, PT\, OnlineInstructor: Krystal Marcinkiew
 icz\, MA\, LPC\, LMHCCurrent Students and Certificate Candidates: CECP 83
 7-2\, 1 semester hour of Graduate Continuing Education credit\, $385.&#16
 0\;Individual Class: We welcome students seeking to take individual cours
 es within the certificate program. Admission to the program is required. 
 Click here for more information (https://www.lclark.edu/programs/continui
 ng_education/certificates/eating_disorders/#Admission)Register Online (ht
 tps://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735425)We are committed to making our events a
 ccessible to all needs and abilities. If you have a disability that may i
 mpact your academic performance\, you may request accommodations by meeti
 ng with the Office of Student Accessibility staff and submitting document
 ation on the Office of Student Accessibility website (/offices/student-ac
 cessibility/). Please be aware that the process for evaluation and implem
 entation of accommodations could take 2-3 weeks\, so please be in touch w
 ith the OSA as soon as possible. Email access@lclark.edu (mailto:access@l
 clark.edu) with any additional questions or concerns.About the Instructor
  Krystal Marcinkiewicz\, MA\, LPC\, LMHC is a Licensed Professional Couns
 elor and Clinical Supervisor\, having earned her Masters Degree in Profes
 sional Mental Health Counseling from Lewis &amp\; Clark College in 2018. 
 Drawing from an integrative feminist approach\, her work is grounded in p
 erson-centered values\, emphasizing authentic connection\, and collaborat
 ive engagement. Her primary clinical focus is supporting clients in navig
 ating identity development\, body politics\, neurodivergence\, emotional 
 codependency\, highly sensitive personalities and other complex emotional
  experiences.  In addition to clinical work\, Krystal is also passionate 
 in training and mentoring emerging counselors. She is an adjunct professo
 r\, teaching a wide variety of graduate counseling courses with an underl
 ying emphasis on counselor identity development\, reflective practice\, a
 nd cultivating professional resilience.  In both the classroom\, and her 
 clinical work\, Krystal is committed to creating affirming spaces that ho
 nor intersectional identities and lived experience.New workshops and trai
 nings are added to our calendar regularly. For the latest on professional
  development related to your specific interests\, sign up for our mailing
  list! (https://lclark.tfaforms.net/4735441)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  As clinician
 s\, we need to be prepared to help clients deconstruct how their bodies h
 ave been storied.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This includes raisin
 g awareness of\, and challenging\, the impact of societal and relational 
 power dynamics. These dynamics impact not only our inner dialog\, but the
  everyday realities of our lives.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This
  course explores how we evaluate our bodies through the lens of "unidenti
 fied others\," as well as the lived experience and consequences of looks\
 , privilege and discrimination.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  Partic
 ipants will consider liberation-based counseling practices to counter the
  objectification\, commodification\, power and gendering of bodies in lat
 e capitalist societies.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  The focus of t
 his course is to raise awareness of body politics in the clinical practic
 e and creating opportunities for change through individual and relational
  wellbeing.</p><p style="line-height: 1.5\;">  This course is part of our
  <a href="https://graduate.lclark.edu/programs/continuing_education/certi
 ficates/eating_disorders/">Eating Disorders Certificate Program</a>.</p><
